NYC 311 Complaints¶

by Dost Karaahmetli¶

Problem Statement¶

The people of New York use 311 system to report complaints about the non-emergency problems to local authorities. Various agencies in New York are assigned these problems. The Department of Housing Preservation and Development (HPD) of New York City is the agency that processes 311 complaints that are related to housing and buildings.

The number of 311 complaints coming to the Department of Housing Preservation and Development has been increasing significantly. Although these complaints are not necessarily urgent, the large volume of complaints and the sudden increase is impacting the overall efficiency of operations of the agency.

This project aims to tackle the requests that are related to housing and buildings which are addressed to HPD, and tries to offer solutions and recommendations to help the agency manage large volume of 311 complaints they are receiving every year.

This project will try to find answers and soutions supported by data and analytics to issues such as:

1. Which type of complaint should HPD focus on first?
2. For the specific type of complaint we have determined, which boroughs and locations (ZIP Codes) should be prioritized?
3. Is there an obvious relationship between the complaint type and any particular characteristic of the properties?
4. Can a predictive model be built for a future prediction of the possibility of complaints type at hand?

- The Data:

The data is from the Department of Housing Preservation and Development of New York City, in CSV format, obtained directly from NYC City Planning Website. Two different datasets are used from this source.

311 complaint dataset:

  • All 311 Service Requests from 2010 to present. This information is automatically updated daily.
  • Dataset consists of: 
      - 22.4 Million rows, each are unique calls (requests) made to 311 Complaint Sevice.
  - 41 Columns
  • More information of the data can be procured from the main dataset documentation page.
  • Dataset will be acquired by using SODA API.
  • For the purposes of the project, the complaints concerning the Housing Preservation and Development Agency (HPD) will be addressed. So, only the data that is related to the HPD will be downloaded and utilized. Also, data will be restricted to the limited number of relevant fields for computational purposes.

PLUTO dataset for housing:

  • Extensive land use and geographic data at the 'tax lot' level in CSV format with more than seventy fields, for the five New York city boroughs: Bronx, Brooklyn, Manhattan, Queens, and Staten Island.
    • Only the part that is specific to the borough that my analysis is interested in will be used for the project. The specific borough will be selected according to prior analysis, so will be decided later.
    • More information about the dataset can be obtained from here.

Note: The project is done under IBM Watson Studio Environment.

We can clearly see that HEAT/HOT WATER is by far the most common problem in NYC concerning housing and buildings. So, The agency's priority should be focusing on HEAT/HOT WATER.

From the domain knowledge gathered from experts, we know that there's a profound similarity between HEAT/HOT WATER and HEATING. From the accumulated general knowledge of the data, we also know that, as of year 2014, HEATING label has been changed as HEATING/HOT WATER. So, bringing these two labels together analyzing them collectively is a good idea.

Similar issue can be observed with "PAINT - PLASTER" and "PAINT/PLASTER" labels, too. So, I'll bring these two together as well.

From the visualization above we can see that;

  • General Construction complaints have not been attended properly, while there are most open cases of this category.
  • Plumbing category displays a similar situation in terms of open case ratio.
  • The agency has done a relatively good job addressing Heat/Hot Water complaints. However, this category still needs to be attended because of the high volume of cases.

Although, the Heat/Hot Water category has more complaints over all, the General Construction and Plumbing categories have more complaints un-attended. So, I'd recommend the agency to tackle these three categories as a priority.

Here we recourse to domain knowledge again...

In the dataset file, it says; "If the NUMBER OF FLOORS is zero and the NUMBER OF BUILDINGS is greater than zero, then NUMBER OF FLOORS is not available for the tax lot. If the NUMBER OF FLOORS is zero and the NUMBER OF BUILDINGS is zero, then NUMBER OF FLOORS is not applicable for the tax lot."

Plus, there's also an explanation about Residential Area which indicates ; "A RESIDENTIAL FLOOR AREA of zero can mean it is either not available or not applicable".

Based on these remarks, I've decided to drop zeros from the 'numfloors' and 'resarea' columns.

def datetimeprocess(df):
    df['Resolution_Time'] = (df['closed_date'] - df['created_date']).dt.days
    df = df[df['Resolution_Time'].notnull()]
    df1 = df[df['closed_date'] >= df['created_date']]
    df1['Day of Week'] = df1['created_date'].dt.dayofweek
    df1['Day of Month'] = df1['created_date'].dt.day
    df1['Month'] = df1['created_date'].dt.month
    df1['Year'] = df1['created_date'].dt.year
    return df1

While considering Linear Regression, the number of complaints will rise in the coming years, whereas they will fall according to the Polynomial Regression analysis.

This is a big issue, since we need to allocate resources aligned with our prediction analysis. We have to be sure which of these regression methods will be more precise, so that we can plan the next three years well enough. For that reason, I examined the plot above again and saw that there is a big jump in the year 2014 and there seems to be different factors effecting the number of complaints before and after 2014. In the light of this assumption, I'll redo my analysis taking the period after 2014 into account.

def getDfSummary(input_data):
    number_nan = input_data.isnull().sum()
    number_distinct = input_data.nunique(dropna=True)
    output_data = pd.DataFrame({'number_nan':number_nan,'number_distinct':number_distinct})
    return output_data

Conclusion¶

We can see from the above confusion matrix and the classification report that Random Forest model is doing fairly good for the first two classes of output. However, because of lack of data points for "more than 10 days", the output show up wrong for third class.

The performance may be improved by performing PCA and adding the "Descriptor" variable which exists in the original NYC 311 Dataset, and employing "one hot encoder" on that variable. We would get a more robust model if we have had more compuatational power which would enable us to perform a broader grid search (code above).
